##My last conversation with Li Wenliang: If I recover, I will be a doctor again

Wechat, bingdianweekly

Features, China Youth Daily's in depth reporting brand. We believe that news has more than one day of life.

Photo of Li Wenliang sent to Yang Hai, a reporter of the China Youth Daily

China Youth Daily China Youth Net reporter Yang Hai

At 2:58 a.m. on February 7, Li Wenliang, an ophthalmologist at Wuhan Central Hospital, died of pneumonia.

On Feb. 2, he posted an update on his condition on the front page, saying that the day before, his new pneumonia nucleic acid test had finally come back positive and his infected parents had been released from the hospital. "thank you for your concern, " he said.

He still retains his signature on Wechat, "theory is gray, the tree of life is evergreen. ".

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Li Wenliang's wechat circle of friends. His wechat profile picture is a crayon caricature of Xiaoxin

On January 31, he gave an interview to a reporter from the China Youth Daily's China Youth Daily website. By this time, he had been in hospital for 19 days. Here is a transcript of our conversation with Li Wenliang:

REPORTER: How is the body condition now?

Li Wenliang: Spirit and appetite a lot better, but still breathing difficulties, can not move, to absolute bed rest. My lungs are slow, but otherwise fine.

Reporter: How did you discover this news of SARS virus at that time? Based on what? Does it reflect up? What did the boss decide?

Li Wenliang: a colleague sent me a test report of a patient. The results of clinical pathogen screening showed that the first positive indicator of high confidence was SARS coronavirus. Because it's not my patient, and I can't report to my superiors.

REPORTER: When do you judge this pneumonia is the person-to-person? Were you scared?

Li Wenliang: On January 9, I received a patient, and then I learned that the patient and his family had been infected one after another, and I was sure that there was a human-to-human transmission. Soon after, on January 10th I myself began to cough, and on January 11th I began to have a fever, at which time I was afraid.

Interviewer: Why are you afraid? What did you think of the virulence of the virus at the time?

Li Wenliang: I'm afraid I can't recover. I consulted my colleagues in respiratory medicine, who thought the virus might not be as virulent as SARS, and reassured me that I was young, that there was no magic bullet, just time.

Reporter: You got the virus information on December 30, why are you still infected?

Li Wenliang: Because I am an ophthalmologist, did not expect so soon contact with the relevant patients, some careless. Now that I think about it, it all happened so fast. So fast.

Reporter: Did you do a viral nucleic acid test after admission? Why didn't you get the test results?

Li Wenliang: I don't know why there hasn't been a definite diagnosis, but I did another test recently and the result is negative.

Interviewer: Have you seen your CT? What's it like?

Li Wenliang: The second time, the image result is already very bad. But that's to be expected. I know there's a progression. I couldn't leave the high-flow oxygen, and I had to breathe on my side for a long, painful time. (reporter's Note: The CT images provided by Li Wenliang showed that by the time of his second examination, about 80% of the lung area had turned white.)

Reporter: Do you think what you say in the Wechat group is a rumor? Why did you sign it?

Li Wenliang: I don't think I'm talking about rumors. I'm a doctor. I believe the test results. And I later stressed that it is coronavirus, the specific typing. I signed because I wanted this to go away. After I got out of the police station, I was still relaxed. After all, I was not detained. I had no idea that so much had happened behind me.

REPORTER: Experts at the CDC say you're honorable. What do you think?

Li Wenliang: I'm just an ordinary person, not a hero. But if people had known about the outbreak earlier, had they protected earlier, they would have been better off.

Reporter: On December 30, after you sent the information about the outbreak to your classmates, did they make any preparations?

Li Wenliang: Many of them bought masks to remind their families. After the screenshot spread, everyone also worried about me, for me to speak up.

Reporter: From when did the hospital begin to inform the doctor to pay attention to the protection? In what form?

Li Wenliang: About January 10, the hospital after the meeting, departments convey that we should pay attention to protection, three-level prevention. But I don't think we were able to achieve full level three protection.

Interviewer: What would you do if you had to do it all over again?

Li Wenliang: I should still remind students to pay attention.

Reporter: Will you be a doctor again after your recovery? Would you let your children choose this career?

Li Wenliang: I will do it again. I have no other skills. But I wouldn't advise my child to become a doctor. The risk is too high.

Interviewer: What do you miss most now?

Li Wenliang: I miss my family most. My parents are still in hospital. My wife is pregnant. It doesn't matter now. I want this outbreak contained and everyone safe.
